15	//        The sandbox plugin internally calls `session:create` to mint the
16	//        session + bearer token (the token flows only into the runner's
17	//        env, never back to us — I9). We do NOT call session:create here;
18	//        `session:create` is not idempotent on sessionId and a double-create
19	//        would throw `duplicate-session`. The orchestrator's contract with
20	//        the sandbox plugin is: "you own session minting, I own the chat
21	//        lifecycle above it."
22	//   5. conversations:bind-session (when ctx.conversationId set) — write
23	//        active_session_id + active_req_id atomically. The SSE handler
24	//        (Task 7) keys off active_req_id to find the in-flight stream.
25	//   6. session:queue-work — enqueue the initial user message
26	//   7. await chat:end event (runner-driven, via IPC server)
27	//   8. cleanup — kill handle if still alive (only on the fresh path)
28	//
29	// The IPC server (Task 4) fires `chat:end` when the runner POSTs
30	// /event.chat-end. The orchestrator's own subscriber captures the outcome
31	// and resolves the awaiting deferred. Error-ish paths (chat:start rejection,
32	// sandbox-open failure, queue-work failure, chat timeout, sandbox early
33	// exit) synthesize a terminated outcome and fire chat:end themselves —
34	// audit-log style subscribers always see exactly one chat:end per agent:invoke.
35	// Happy-path chat:end is fired by the IPC server, NOT the orchestrator;
36	// double-firing would double-count in audit-log.
37	//
38	// Invariants:
39	//   I1 — Hook payloads are backend-agnostic. Input is `{ message, maxTurns? }`,
40	//        output is AgentOutcome — no transport / storage vocabulary (no
41	//        runnerEndpoint, sessionId leakage, etc.). sessionId exists on
42	//        AgentContext already, which is the kernel-level primitive.
43	//   I5 — Capabilities explicit. The orchestrator only calls the exact hooks
44	//        in its manifest (session:queue-work / session:terminate /
45	//        sandbox:open-session). It does NOT spawn, it does NOT
46	//        touch the filesystem, it does NOT open sockets. Those are
47	//        sandbox-subprocess / ipc-server's jobs.
48	// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
49	
50	export interface ChatOrchestratorConfig {
51	  // Absolute path to the runner's dist/main.js. Passed through to
52	  // sandbox:open-session — we don't validate here; the sandbox plugin does.
53	  runnerBinary: string;
54	  // Bounded wait for chat:end. Defaults to 10 min. If the runner crashes or
55	  // hangs without emitting chat-end, we synthesize a terminated outcome
56	  // after this elapses.
57	  chatTimeoutMs?: number;
58	  // One-shot mode (default true for 6.5a): on the first `chat:turn-end` the
59	  // orchestrator queues a `cancel` entry into the runner's inbox, so the
60	  // runner exits cleanly after processing the single user message and emits
61	  // its final `event.chat-end`. Callers driving multi-message sessions set
62	  // this to false and queue additional user messages themselves.
63	  //
64	  // Why this lives here: the runner is persistent by design (design doc
65	  // §"Runner comparison") so it can service future multi-message flows.
66	  // Week 6.5a's only caller (the CLI) is one-shot. Rather than bifurcate the
67	  // runner's behavior, the orchestrator owns the "this chat is done" signal.
68	  oneShot?: boolean;
69	}
70	
71	export interface ChatRunInput {
72	  message: ChatMessage;
73	  // Forwarded to the runner's turn loop eventually. For 6.5a the runner has
74	  // its own default; the orchestrator currently ignores maxTurns for dispatch
75	  // but preserves the field name so the shape lines up with Week 4-6's
76	  // chat-loop.ts caller contract.
77	  maxTurns?: number;
78	}
